#Text=John
#Text=Hales ( died 1540 )
#Text=For other people with the same name , see John Hales ( disambiguation ) .
#Text=Arms of Hales : Gules , three arrows or feathered and barbed argent
#Text=John Hales ( by 1470 – 1540 ) , of The Dungeon in the parish of St. Mary Bredin , [ 1 ]
#Text=Canterbury , Kent , was an administrator , politician and judge [ 2 ] [ 3 ] [ 4 ] who was appointed a Baron of the Exchequer in 1522 .
#Text=Origins
#Text=He was born before 1470 , [ 5 ] a son of John Hales , of Tenterden in Kent , and a brother of Sir John Hales ( d.1555 ) , a Justice of the Common Pleas .
#Text=His mother 's name is not recorded .
#Text=His grandfather was Henry Hales , of Hales Place at Halden in Tenterden , who married Juliana Capell , a daughter of Richard Capell of Lenden in Tenterden . [ 6 ]
#Text=His great-uncle Thomas Hales was the father of the judge Sir Christopher Hales , [ 7 ]
#Text=Master of the Rolls .
#Text=Career
#Text=Probably admitted to legal studies at Gray 's Inn about 1490 , by 1501 he had been appointed steward of the Priory of Christ Church at Canterbury .
#Text=In 1503 he was made a justice of the peace for Kent , and in 1504 was appointed counsel to the corporation of Rye , [ 3 ] and was also elected bailiff of his home town of Tenterden .
#Text=From 1508 , he was appointed to various royal commissions in his native Kent , in Middlesex and Sussex , and across the Channel in the English possessions of Calais and Guînes . [ 4 ]
#Text=By 1509 he had residences at both Canterbury , where he had acquired the manor known as The Dungeon just outside the city walls , and at Nackington . [ 8 ]
#Text=In 1512 and again in 1515 he was elected a member of parliament for Canterbury , and was also retained as counsel to the corporation of Canterbury .
#Text=In addition to legal work for the city , he was also employed in drafting legislation for the government . [ 4 ]
#Text=He became a Bencher of Gray 's Inn in 1514 , [ 9 ] giving lectures in that year and in 1520 . [ 4 ]
#Text=His further advancement was probably the result of patronage by Sir Henry Guildford , the Comptroller of the Household , [ 8 ]
#Text=In 1519 he was appointed Attorney-General to the Duchy of Lancaster , [ 3 ] in about 1520 steward of St Augustine 's Abbey , [ 4 ] and in 1521 general surveyor of Crown lands .
#Text=He retained the last , but gave up the Duchy post when he was appointed third Baron of the Exchequer in 1522 . [ 3 ]
#Text=To this was added the responsibility of justice of the peace for Middlesex and Sussex in 1524 .
#Text=As a judge , he was no longer eligible for parliament and in 1523 his seat was taken by his cousin Sir Christopher . [ 4 ]
#Text=After six years in that office , he was appointed second Baron in 1528 but was passed over for Chief Baron the following year . [ 8 ] [ 4 ]
#Text=He retired from his judicial position in November 1539 and made his will on 20 July 1540 , asking to be buried beside his wife in his parish church of St Mary Bredin at Canterbury .
#Text=His will bequeathed gold coins to his four surviving sons , his best gold ring to his cousin Sir Christopher , and a gold ring to his daughter Mildred . [ 3 ] [ 10 ] [ 11 ]
#Text=He must have died shortly after , but no date survives . [ 4 ]
#Text=Family
#Text=By 1509 he was married to Isabel , daughter and coheiress of Stephen Harry and his wife Isabel , daughter and heiress of William Brooker . [ 12 ] [ 13 ]
#Text=They had four sons and a daughter : [ 14 ]
#Text=James , of The Dungeon . [ 4 ]
#Text=Thomas , of Thanington .
#Text=Edward , of Tenterden , who married Margaret , the daughter of John Honywood , of Sene in Hythe , [ 15 ] and was the grandfather of Sir Edward Hales , 1st Baronet . [ 16 ]
#Text=William , of Nackington . [ 17 ] Mildred , [ 4 ] who married as his first wife John Honywood of Sene in Hythe . [ 15 ]
